The Ukraine on its way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and they will never meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
The Ukraine is undoubtedly located in the East, but in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the predominant goal for many of us.
The way there was not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
But the results of the parliamentary elections on March 31 have shown that Ukrainians are still determined to follow this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It is beyond doubt for me that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine faces in finding its way to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry, as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machine parks and the inertia of the state-led agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We have completely messed up the reform on our own.
Because often we wanted to import tested concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict respect for human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy - in a weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Verkhovna Rada (the parliament of Ukraine) has adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights over the years, which is equivalent to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that was cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but it has gained momentum, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as more open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Yet, we are Europeans.
This can be seen on the streets and squares of Kiev.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, just like in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to be careful around reckless drivers).
In Kiev, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public spaces where people can stop and enjoy life.
Young people are learning English, German, and French, they can work with computers and surf the internet in internet cafes.
But these are just the romantic sidelines of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The sober view of a professional politician, which I am, sees more profound changes.
In the last ten years, a development has taken place from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption, and finally to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very vividly.
Initially, the reform of the state evoked a hostile mood both among bureaucrats and among ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction in the number of public servants began.
It was a "template F" reform: the state must shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland manage to thrive with large government apparatuses.
The problem is not just one of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by cutting costs led us to the second stage in our reform process.
The state was slowly reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for ministers were established with a clearly defined area of responsibility.
As a result, the work of government ministries has been stabilized.
Initially, the authority transferred to these new areas was a bit too broad to make their work more effective.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians might sometimes get annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (if reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of whom there are still too many among us - can afford to take a indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. Because radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial can by no means admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
The more we shed our provincial impulse to defend ourselves, the more we open ourselves to the best that others can offer us.
About a century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe".
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to recognize that their country had inherited this unfortunate title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even weaker, but the recent elections, which brought the communists to a minority position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "strong parties" under President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the periphery of politics.
The reform parties and European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society where there are no outsiders or outcasts.
As the great and at the time already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long and arduous path to Europe has helped a weak new nation become strong and survive.
